english:
  title: On Discernment
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I hold non-attachment as my treasure,
    with nothing at all clinging to my heart.
    Gold and pearls before my eyes appear as mud—
    I see them yet see them not; how much less would I grasp them.

    Yet ink and paper—what virtue do they possess
    that my hands cannot release them?
    Where desire dwells in the heart, there dwells no purity;
    this longing has become an affliction I cannot escape.

    In life, whether foolish or wise, who bears no burden?
    Some cherish fine inkstones, others prefer worthless trinkets.
    But Lee Taekji, my friend of a hundred years,
    shares my tastes—truly a kindred spirit without measure.

    He traveled beyond the Yi River to misty Youyan,
    and sent me a piece of dark, perfect jade.
    I open the inkstone, dust it reverently, yet cannot bear to grind it—
    I think still of Teinkyu's ancient hand.

    Another friend, knowing what I cherish,
    sent a hundred sheets of official paper strung together.
    The surplus from imperial edicts, he said—
    white as snow when spread upon my desk.

    Though these things seem trivial to common eyes,
    those who love them through the ages are no ordinary folk.
    The kindness of these two friends moves me deeply,
    yet I wonder if I deserve such grace.

    Since then, in decline and solitude on South Mountain,
    my Green Pavilion grows emptier day by day.
    Though I lack the skill of great calligraphers,
    I know something of arrangement and form.

    If only someone would lend me a single brush hair
    to paint the scarlet sincerity of my lifetime.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yi River and Youyan: References to classical Chinese geography and journeys of worthy recluses.'
    - 'Teinkyu (廷珪): A renowned ancient Chinese inkstone carver, representing excellence in craftsmanship.'
    - The poem addresses the paradox of renouncing material desires while being attached to refined cultural objects—ink, paper, and inkstones used for calligraphy and scholarship.
